  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(22) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Let him be crucified.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—It may be noted that this was the first direct intimation of the mode of death to which the priests destined their prisoner. It was implied, indeed, in their fixed resolve to make the Roman governor the executioner of their sentence, as shown in the dialogue recorded by St. John (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 18:31",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); but now the cry came from the multitude, as the result, we may believe, of the promptings described in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 27:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “Crucify Him!”—punish Him as the robber and the rebel are punished.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
